{
  "The primary site of nutrient absorption in the GI tract is the:": "",
  "Esophagus": "",
  "Stomach": "",
  "Small intestine": "",
  "Large intestine": "",
  "The small intestine is the primary site of nutrient absorption due to its enormous surface area created by plicae circulares, villi, and microvilli, which together provide approximately 200 square meters of absorptive surface.": "",
  "Villi and microvilli increase the small intestine's absorptive surface area to approximately:": "",
  "200 square meters": "",
  "10 square meters": "",
  "1000 square meters": "",
  "50 square meters": "",
  "The combination of circular folds, villi, and microvilli increases the absorptive surface area of the small intestine to roughly 200 square meters, approximately the size of a tennis court, which is essential for efficient nutrient uptake.": "",
  "Monosaccharides such as glucose and galactose are absorbed into:": "",
  "Blood capillaries in the villi, then transported via the hepatic portal vein to the liver": "",
  "Directly into the systemic circulation via the vena cava": "",
  "Lymphatic vessels only": "",
  "Lacteals in the villi": "",
  "Water-soluble nutrients including monosaccharides and amino acids are absorbed into the blood capillaries within each villus and travel via the hepatic portal vein to the liver, where they undergo first-pass metabolism before entering the general circulation.": "",
  "Dietary fats are absorbed into enterocytes and then transported via:": "",
  "Blood capillaries directly to the liver": "",
  "Nerve fibers in the villi": "",
  "The hepatic portal vein as free fatty acids": "",
  "Lacteals as chylomicrons, entering the lymphatic system": "",
  "After absorption into enterocytes, long-chain fatty acids and monoglycerides are reassembled into triglycerides, packaged into chylomicrons, and released into lacteals (lymphatic capillaries), eventually entering the bloodstream via the thoracic duct.": "",
  "Vitamin B12 absorption requires which substance produced by parietal cells?": "",
  "Hydrochloric acid": "",
  "Bile salts": "",
  "Pepsinogen": "",
  "Intrinsic factor": "",
  "Intrinsic factor, produced by gastric parietal cells, binds to vitamin B12 and forms a complex that is specifically recognized by receptors in the terminal ileum, making it essential for B12 absorption.": "",
  "Fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) are absorbed along with:": "",
  "Water in the large intestine": "",
  "Dietary fats, requiring bile salts for their absorption": "",
  "Glucose via sodium co-transport": "",
  "Amino acids via active transport": "",
  "Fat-soluble vitamins dissolve in dietary lipids and are incorporated into micelles formed by bile salts, which carry them to the enterocyte brush border for absorption. Any condition impairing fat absorption will also cause fat-soluble vitamin deficiency.": "",
  "Iron is primarily absorbed in which segment of the small intestine?": "",
  "Duodenum and proximal jejunum": "",
  "Ileum and terminal small intestine": "",
  "Distal jejunum and mid-small intestine only": "",
  "Cecum and proximal large intestine": "",
  "Iron absorption occurs primarily in the duodenum and proximal jejunum, where the acidic environment from gastric acid helps maintain iron in its more absorbable ferrous (Fe2+) form.": "",
  "The hepatic portal system carries absorbed nutrients from the GI tract to the:": "",
  "Heart for oxygenation and systemic distribution to tissues": "",
  "Liver for processing, detoxification, and metabolism": "",
  "Kidneys for filtration, reabsorption, and waste excretion": "",
  "Lungs for oxygenation of venous blood returning from tissues": "",
  "The hepatic portal vein collects nutrient-rich blood from the GI tract and delivers it to the liver, which serves as the body's metabolic processing center for first-pass metabolism, nutrient storage, and detoxification before nutrients enter the systemic circulation.": "",
  "The large intestine primarily absorbs:": "",
  "Proteins and fats": "",
  "Remaining water and electrolytes from indigestible residue": "",
  "Bile salts and vitamins": "",
  "Glucose and amino acids": "",
  "The large intestine absorbs most of the remaining water and electrolytes (especially sodium and chloride) from the indigestible food residue, concentrating the waste material into solid feces for elimination.": "",
  "Calcium absorption in the small intestine is enhanced by:": "",
  "High dietary fiber intake": "",
  "Low stomach acid levels": "",
  "Vitamin D and parathyroid hormone (PTH)": "",
  "Excess dietary iron": "",
  "Active vitamin D (calcitriol) upregulates the expression of calcium-binding proteins (calbindin) in enterocytes, while PTH indirectly enhances calcium absorption by stimulating the kidneys to produce more active vitamin D.": "",
  "What is a chylomicron?": "",
  "A large lipoprotein particle assembled in enterocytes that transports dietary triglycerides and fat-soluble vitamins through the lymphatic system": "",
  "A hormone secreted by the small intestine to regulate fat digestion": "",
  "A digestive enzyme that breaks down fats in the duodenum": "",
  "A type of white blood cell found in the gut-associated lymphoid tissue": "",
  "Chylomicrons are the largest lipoproteins, assembled within enterocytes from absorbed fatty acids, monoglycerides, cholesterol, and fat-soluble vitamins. They are too large to enter blood capillaries directly and instead enter lacteals, traveling through the lymphatic system to reach the bloodstream.": "",
  "What is a lacteal?": "",
  "A type of gland cell in the stomach lining": "",
  "A lymphatic capillary within each intestinal villus that absorbs dietary fats packaged as chylomicrons": "",
  "A blood capillary within each intestinal villus that absorbs sugars": "",
  "An enzyme in breast milk that aids infant digestion": "",
  "A lacteal is a specialized lymphatic capillary located in the core of each intestinal villus. It receives chylomicrons containing absorbed dietary fats, giving the lymph a milky white appearance called chyle, which drains into larger lymphatic vessels and eventually enters the blood.": "",
  "What does the term 'malabsorption' mean?": "",
  "A condition in which the stomach absorbs too many toxins": "",
  "The excessive absorption of water in the colon leading to constipation": "",
  "The impaired ability of the small intestine to adequately absorb nutrients, vitamins, or minerals from the diet": "",
  "The overproduction of digestive enzymes by the pancreas": "",
  "Malabsorption refers to any condition in which the small intestine fails to adequately absorb one or more nutrients from digested food. It can result from mucosal damage (celiac disease), enzyme deficiency, surgical resection, or other pathologies, leading to weight loss, diarrhea, and nutrient deficiencies.": "",
  "What is the hepatic portal vein?": "",
  "A lymphatic vessel that drains the liver": "",
  "An artery that supplies blood to the small intestine": "",
  "A large vein that carries nutrient-rich, deoxygenated blood from the GI tract and spleen directly to the liver for processing": "",
  "A vein that carries oxygenated blood from the lungs to the liver": "",
  "The hepatic portal vein is unique because it connects two capillary beds: the capillaries of the GI tract and spleen drain into this vein, which then branches into sinusoidal capillaries in the liver. This portal system ensures all absorbed nutrients pass through the liver for first-pass metabolism before reaching systemic circulation.": "",
  "What does 'active transport' mean in the context of nutrient absorption?": "",
  "The bulk flow of fluid through gaps between epithelial cells": "",
  "The energy-requiring movement of substances across a cell membrane against their concentration gradient, using ATP or ion gradients": "",
  "The movement of substances across a membrane down their concentration gradient without energy input": "",
  "The engulfment of large particles by enterocytes through phagocytosis": "",
  "Active transport requires cellular energy (ATP) to move substances against their concentration gradient. In the small intestine, many nutrients such as glucose (via SGLT1) and amino acids are absorbed using sodium-dependent active co-transport on the apical membrane of enterocytes.": "",
  "What is an enterocyte?": "",
  "The primary absorptive epithelial cell lining the small intestine, featuring a brush border of microvilli": "",
  "A type of immune cell that patrols the intestinal lumen": "",
  "A hormone-secreting cell in the gastric glands": "",
  "A nerve cell within the enteric nervous system": "",
  "Enterocytes are the columnar epithelial cells that line the intestinal villi and are responsible for nutrient absorption. Their apical surface is covered with thousands of microvilli (the brush border) that contain digestive enzymes and transport proteins, and they have a rapid turnover rate of approximately 3 to 5 days.": "",
  "What does 'first-pass metabolism' mean?": "",
  "The metabolism of absorbed substances by the liver before they reach the systemic circulation, reducing their bioavailability": "",
  "The initial digestion of food in the mouth by salivary enzymes": "",
  "The first wave of peristalsis after eating a meal": "",
  "The rapid absorption of glucose in the duodenum before it reaches the jejunum": "",
  "First-pass metabolism (also called the first-pass effect) occurs when substances absorbed from the GI tract pass through the liver via the hepatic portal vein before entering systemic circulation. The liver can metabolize, modify, or detoxify these substances, significantly reducing the amount that reaches the rest of the body.": "",
  "What is the gut microbiome?": "",
  "The network of blood vessels supplying the intestinal wall": "",
  "The collection of digestive enzymes produced by the pancreas": "",
  "The vast community of trillions of microorganisms (bacteria, fungi, viruses) residing primarily in the large intestine that aids digestion, synthesizes vitamins, and supports immunity": "",
  "The layer of mucus coating the stomach lining that protects against acid": "",
  "The gut microbiome consists of trillions of microorganisms that colonize the GI tract, predominantly the large intestine. These beneficial microbes ferment indigestible fibers, produce short-chain fatty acids, synthesize vitamins K and biotin, help train the immune system, and protect against pathogenic organisms.": "",
  "What does 'osmosis' mean in the context of intestinal water absorption?": "",
  "The filtration of water through the glomerulus in the kidney": "",
  "The passive movement of water across a semipermeable membrane from an area of lower solute concentration to an area of higher solute concentration": "",
  "The active pumping of water molecules across cell membranes using ATP": "",
  "The secretion of water into the intestinal lumen by goblet cells": "",
  "Osmosis is the movement of water across a semipermeable membrane toward the side with higher solute concentration. In the intestine, when sodium and other solutes are actively absorbed, water follows osmotically, making solute absorption the driving force behind water absorption.": "",
  "What is oral rehydration therapy (ORT)?": "",
  "An intravenous fluid replacement given only in hospitals": "",
  "A medication that stops diarrhea by slowing gut motility": "",
  "An antibiotic solution that kills bacteria causing diarrheal illness": "",
  "A solution of water, salts (sodium), and glucose given by mouth that exploits the sodium-glucose co-transporter to drive water absorption and treat dehydration": "",
  "ORT works by taking advantage of the SGLT1 sodium-glucose co-transporter on enterocytes. When glucose and sodium are absorbed together, water follows osmotically, allowing effective rehydration even during severe diarrhea. ORT has saved millions of lives globally, particularly in children in developing countries.": "",
  "A patient with celiac disease presents with chronic diarrhea, weight loss, and iron-deficiency anemia. A duodenal biopsy reveals flattened villi. Which mechanism best explains why this patient is malnourished?": "",
  "Immune-mediated destruction of intestinal villi dramatically reduces the absorptive surface area, leading to malabsorption of nutrients, vitamins, and minerals": "",
  "The patient has excessive gastric acid production destroying nutrients before absorption": "",
  "The large intestine is absorbing too much water, leaving no fluid for nutrient transport": "",
  "The patient's liver is failing to produce bile, preventing all digestion": "",
  "In celiac disease, an autoimmune reaction to gluten destroys the intestinal villi and microvilli, reducing the absorptive surface area from approximately 200 square meters to a fraction of that. This villous atrophy leads to widespread malabsorption of iron, calcium, fat-soluble vitamins, folate, and other essential nutrients.": "",
  "A physician prescribes iron supplements to a patient with iron-deficiency anemia and advises taking them with orange juice rather than with milk or antacids. What is the physiological rationale for this advice?": "",
  "The sugar in orange juice provides energy for active iron transport": "",
  "Vitamin C in orange juice reduces ferric iron (Fe3+) to ferrous iron (Fe2+), its more absorbable form, while calcium and antacids inhibit iron absorption": "",
  "Orange juice stimulates bile secretion, which carries iron to the intestine": "",
  "Orange juice acidifies the stomach, which destroys competing bacteria that consume iron": "",
  "Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) is a potent reducing agent that converts ferric iron (Fe3+) to ferrous iron (Fe2+), which is the form recognized by the DMT1 transporter on enterocytes in the duodenum. Calcium and alkaline substances like antacids interfere with iron absorption, so they should be taken at different times.": "",
  "A patient who underwent a total gastrectomy (complete stomach removal) develops megaloblastic anemia several years after surgery. Which nutrient deficiency most likely explains this finding, and why?": "",
  "Vitamin C deficiency, because the stomach normally produces vitamin C": "",
  "Calcium deficiency, because the stomach is where calcium is primarily absorbed": "",
  "Iron deficiency, because the stomach is the primary site of iron absorption": "",
  "Vitamin B12 deficiency, because parietal cells that produce intrinsic factor (required for B12 absorption in the ileum) are no longer present": "",
  "Without the stomach, there are no parietal cells to produce intrinsic factor, which is essential for binding and absorbing vitamin B12 in the terminal ileum. Because the body stores B12 for several years, megaloblastic anemia typically develops 3 to 5 years after gastrectomy, requiring lifelong B12 injections.": "",
  "A child in a developing country with severe diarrhea is brought to a clinic. The healthcare provider prepares a simple solution of clean water, salt, and sugar to give by mouth. How does this oral rehydration solution work at the cellular level?": "",
  "The sugar kills bacteria in the gut, stopping the diarrhea": "",
  "The salt directly plugs the ion channels responsible for fluid secretion": "",
  "Glucose and sodium are co-absorbed via the SGLT1 transporter on enterocytes, and water follows osmotically, restoring fluid balance": "",
  "The sugar coats the intestinal lining and prevents further fluid loss": "",
  "The SGLT1 sodium-glucose co-transporter on the apical membrane of enterocytes simultaneously absorbs one glucose molecule and two sodium ions. This creates an osmotic gradient that draws water from the lumen into the cell and then into the bloodstream, enabling rehydration even when diarrhea is ongoing.": "",
  "A patient with Crohn's disease affecting the terminal ileum reports chronic diarrhea and steatorrhea (fatty stools). The physician explains that the diseased ileum cannot reabsorb bile salts. Why does this lead to fat malabsorption?": "",
  "Bile salts are the enzymes that chemically digest fat, so their loss means no fat breakdown can occur": "",
  "The lost bile salts deplete the bile salt pool, reducing the amount available for fat emulsification in the duodenum, leading to impaired fat digestion and absorption": "",
  "Without bile salts, the stomach cannot produce enough acid to begin fat digestion": "",
  "Without bile salt reabsorption, the liver cannot produce new bile salts, and fat digestion stops entirely": "",
  "Normally, about 95% of bile salts are reabsorbed in the terminal ileum via the enterohepatic circulation and recycled back to the liver. When the ileum is diseased, bile salts are lost in the stool, depleting the bile salt pool faster than the liver can synthesize replacements, resulting in inadequate fat emulsification and steatorrhea.": "",
  "A nursing student notices that a patient receiving total parenteral nutrition (TPN) through a central IV line has not eaten anything by mouth for three weeks. The student asks why the patient's intestinal villi may be atrophying. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "The IV nutrients are toxic to the intestinal lining": "",
  "The lack of bile secretion during TPN dissolves the villous structure": "",
  "TPN causes excessive gastric acid secretion that erodes the villi": "",
  "Without luminal nutrients to stimulate enterocyte turnover and trophic hormones, the intestinal mucosa undergoes disuse atrophy": "",
  "The intestinal mucosa requires luminal nutrients and trophic signals (such as those from CCK, secretin, and direct nutrient contact) to maintain its structure and rapid cell turnover. Prolonged absence of enteral feeding leads to villous atrophy, which is why clinicians try to restore oral or enteral feeding as soon as possible.": "",
  "A patient who had a large portion of the jejunum surgically removed develops chronic diarrhea, weight loss, and multiple vitamin deficiencies. The doctor diagnoses short bowel syndrome. Why does removing a large segment of small intestine cause these problems?": "",
  "The reduced intestinal length provides insufficient absorptive surface area and transit time for adequate nutrient and fluid absorption": "",
  "The surgical removal destroys the enteric nervous system, stopping peristalsis entirely": "",
  "The liver stops producing bile after jejunal resection": "",
  "The remaining intestine produces too much mucus, blocking absorption": "",
  "Short bowel syndrome occurs when there is insufficient remaining intestinal length to absorb adequate nutrients, fluids, and electrolytes. The jejunum is the primary site for most nutrient absorption, so its loss drastically reduces absorptive capacity, often requiring long-term parenteral nutrition support.": "",
  "A 65-year-old woman with osteoporosis is told by her doctor that her low vitamin D levels are contributing to her bone loss because vitamin D is essential for calcium absorption. She asks which part of the digestive system is involved. What is the correct answer?": "",
  "The stomach, where calcium is absorbed with the help of HCl": "",
  "The duodenum and jejunum, where active vitamin D promotes the expression of calcium-binding proteins in enterocytes for calcium absorption": "",
  "The large intestine, which is the main site for mineral absorption": "",
  "The gallbladder, which stores calcium before releasing it into the blood": "",
  "Active vitamin D (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D or calcitriol) acts on enterocytes in the duodenum and jejunum to upregulate calbindin, a calcium-binding protein that facilitates transcellular calcium absorption. Without adequate vitamin D, calcium absorption drops significantly, contributing to osteoporosis.": "",
  "A medical student is studying a patient with liver cirrhosis who has ascites (abdominal fluid accumulation) and edema. The attending physician explains that the liver's reduced ability to synthesize a specific protein is contributing to these findings. Which protein is most likely involved?": "",
  "Intrinsic factor, which is needed for B12 absorption": "",
  "Hemoglobin": "",
  "Pepsinogen, which is needed for protein digestion": "",
  "Albumin, which maintains plasma oncotic pressure that keeps fluid within blood vessels": "",
  "Albumin is the most abundant plasma protein and is synthesized almost exclusively by the liver. It is the primary determinant of plasma oncotic (colloid osmotic) pressure. When the cirrhotic liver cannot produce enough albumin, oncotic pressure drops and fluid leaks from blood vessels into tissues (edema) and the peritoneal cavity (ascites).": "",
  "A researcher is studying a newly discovered genetic disorder in which the SGLT1 sodium-glucose co-transporter is nonfunctional in the small intestine. Which clinical findings would you expect in an infant born with this condition?": "",
  "Excessive iron absorption leading to iron overload and liver damage": "",
  "Inability to digest proteins, leading to protein malnutrition": "",
  "Severe osmotic diarrhea and dehydration when fed glucose or galactose, because these sugars remain unabsorbed in the intestinal lumen": "",
  "Fat malabsorption and steatorrhea, because SGLT1 is required for lipid transport": "",
  "This condition, known as glucose-galactose malabsorption, results from mutations in the SGLT1 transporter. Without functional SGLT1, glucose and galactose cannot be actively absorbed in the small intestine. These unabsorbed sugars draw water osmotically into the lumen, causing severe watery diarrhea that can be life-threatening if untreated. Affected infants must be fed fructose-based formulas since fructose is absorbed by a different transporter (GLUT5).": ""
}